(Bojan): In theory, they are the same. 



In practice, you would be doing two transactions versus one, which would probably have higher overall cost (option premium spread + broker/exchange fee against just option premium spread).

(You): thanks. That was the one difference I noticed too. However, if you're 'put' on the put, you end up w/ a short position you have to liquidate, which costs commission/spread. Of course, holding a short put also means no rollover costs (but sometimes rollover is positive, and I'll bet those costs are incorporated into the put). Basically, I'm writing covered calls right now (Forex), but am thinking about switching to naked puts. The latter SEEMS more dangerous, but I'm not sure why. [direct gchat: carter.barry@gmail.com]

(Bojan): If you write a covered put, you can lose as much as you paid for you position. With naked put, you can lose way more. 



Say, you got long eur that you bought at 1.30.  You sell a put at 1.20, market at 1.15.  Most you can lose is .10, and that's if the market goes above 1.20. If it was a naked position, your loss would be the difference between market price and strike. 



And for rolls, they are spreaded daily, you want to stay away from that (unless you find no spread broker).  Maybe use loan/deposit to carry the position forward.  



